# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: molecular-orbital-theory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/antibonding-molecular-orbital] In theoretical chemistry, an **antibonding orbital** is a type of molecular orbital that weakens the chemical bond between two atoms and helps to raise the energy of the molecule relative to the separated atoms.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/antibonding-molecular-orbital] Such an orbital has one or more nodes in the bonding region between the nuclei.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/antibonding-molecular-orbital] The density of the electrons in the orbital is concentrated outside the bonding region and acts to pull one nucleus away from the other and tends to cause mutual repulsion between the two atoms.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/antibonding-molecular-orbital] This is in contrast to a bonding molecular orbital, which has a lower energy than that of the separate atoms, and is responsible for chemical bonds.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/antibonding-molecular-orbital] Antibonding molecular orbitals (MOs) are normally *higher* in energy than bonding molecular orbitals.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/antibonding-molecular-orbital] Bonding and antibonding orbitals form when atoms combine into molecules.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/antibonding-molecular-orbital] If two hydrogen atoms are initially far apart, they have identical atomic orbitals.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/antibonding-molecular-orbital] However, as the spacing between the two atoms becomes smaller, the electron wave functions begin to overlap.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/antibonding-molecular-orbital] The Pauli exclusion principle prohibits any two electrons (e-) in a molecule from having the same set of quantum numbers.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/antibonding-molecular-orbital] Therefore each original atomic orbital of the isolated atoms (for example, the ground state energy level, 1*s*) splits into two molecular orbitals belonging to the pair, one lower in energy than the original atomic level and one higher.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/antibonding-molecular-orbital] The orbital which is in a lower energy state than the orbitals of the separate atoms is the bonding orbital, which is more stable and promotes the bonding of the two H atoms into H2.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/antibonding-molecular-orbital] The higher-energy orbital is the antibonding orbital, which is less stable and opposes bonding if it is occupied.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/antibonding-molecular-orbital] In a molecule such as H2, the two electrons normally occupy the lower-energy bonding orbital, so that the molecule is more stable than the separate H atoms.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/antibonding-molecular-orbital] A molecular orbital becomes antibonding when there is less electron density between the two nuclei than there would be if there were no bonding interaction at all.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/antibonding-molecular-orbital] When a molecular orbital changes sign (from positive to negative) at a *nodal plane* between two atoms, it is said to be *antibonding with respect to those atoms*.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/antibonding-molecular-orbital] Antibonding orbitals are often labelled with an asterisk (*) on molecular orbital diagrams.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/antibonding-molecular-orbital] In homonuclear diatomic molecules, σ* (*sigma star*) antibonding orbitals have no nodal planes passing through the two nuclei, like sigma bonds, and π* (*pi star*) orbitals have one nodal plane passing through the two nuclei, like pi bonds.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/antibonding-molecular-orbital] The Pauli exclusion principle dictates that no two electrons in an interacting system may have the same quantum state.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/antibonding-molecular-orbital] If the bonding orbitals are filled, then any additional electrons will occupy antibonding orbitals.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/antibonding-molecular-orbital] This occurs in the He2 molecule, in which both the 1sσ and 1sσ* orbitals are filled.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/antibonding-molecular-orbital] Since the *antibonding orbital is more antibonding than the bonding orbital is bonding*, the molecule has a higher energy than two separated helium atoms, and it is therefore unstable.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/antibonding-molecular-orbital] In molecules with several atoms, some orbitals may be delocalized over more than two atoms.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/antibonding-molecular-orbital] A particular molecular orbital may be *bonding with respect to some adjacent pairs of atoms* and *antibonding with respect to other pairs*.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/antibonding-molecular-orbital] If the bonding interactions outnumber the antibonding interactions, the MO is said to be *bonding*, whereas, if the antibonding interactions outnumber the bonding interactions, the molecular orbital is said to be *antibonding*.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/antibonding-molecular-orbital] For example, butadiene has pi orbitals which are delocalized over all four carbon atoms.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/antibonding-molecular-orbital] There are two bonding pi orbitals which are occupied in the ground state: π1 is bonding between all carbons, while π2 is bonding between C1 and C2 and between C3 and C4, and antibonding between C2 and C3.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/antibonding-molecular-orbital] There are also antibonding pi orbitals with two and three antibonding interactions as shown in the diagram; these are vacant in the ground state, but may be occupied in excited states.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/antibonding-molecular-orbital] Similarly benzene with six carbon atoms has three bonding pi orbitals and three antibonding pi orbitals.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/antibonding-molecular-orbital] Since each carbon atom contributes one electron to the π-system of benzene, there are six pi electrons which fill the three lowest-energy pi molecular orbitals (the bonding pi orbitals).
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/antibonding-molecular-orbital] Antibonding orbitals are also important for explaining chemical reactions in terms of molecular orbital theory.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/antibonding-molecular-orbital] Roald Hoffmann and Kenichi Fukui shared the 1981 Nobel Prize in Chemistry for their work and further development of qualitative molecular orbital explanations for chemical reactions.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] In chemistry, **bond order** is a formal measure of the multiplicity of a covalent bond between two atoms.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] As introduced by Gerhard Herzberg, building off of work by R.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] Mulliken and Friedrich Hund, bond order is defined as the difference between the numbers of electron pairs in bonding and antibonding molecular orbitals.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] Bond order gives a rough indication of the stability of a bond.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] Isoelectronic species have the same bond order.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] The bond order itself is the number of electron pairs (covalent bonds) between two atoms.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] For example, in diatomic nitrogen N≡N, the bond order between the two nitrogen atoms is 3 (triple bond).
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] In acetylene H–C≡C–H, the bond order between the two carbon atoms is also 3, and the C–H bond order is 1 (single bond).
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] In carbon monoxide, −C≡O+, the bond order between carbon and oxygen is 3.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] In thiazyl trifluoride N≡SF3, the bond order between sulfur and nitrogen is 3, and between sulfur and fluorine is 1.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] In diatomic oxygen O=O the bond order is 2 (double bond).
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] In ethylene H2C=CH2 the bond order between the two carbon atoms is also 2.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] The bond order between carbon and oxygen in carbon dioxide O=C=O is also 2.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] In phosgene O=CCl2, the bond order between carbon and oxygen is 2, and between carbon and chlorine is 1.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] In some molecules, bond orders can be 4 (quadruple bond), 5 (quintuple bond) or even 6 (sextuple bond).
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] For example, potassium octachlorodimolybdate salt (K4[Mo2Cl8]) contains the [Cl4Mo≣MoCl4]4− anion, in which the two Mo atoms are linked to each other by a bond with an order of 4.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] Each Mo atom is linked to four Cl− ligands by a bond with an order of 1.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] The compound (terphenyl)–CrCr–(terphenyl) contains two chromium atoms linked to each other by a bond with an order of 5, and each chromium atom is linked to one terphenyl ligand by a single bond.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] A bond of order 6 is detected in ditungsten molecules W2, which exist only in a gaseous phase.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] In molecules which have resonance, bond order may not be an integer.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] In benzene, the delocalized molecular orbitals contain 6 pi electrons over six carbons, essentially yielding half a pi bond together with the sigma bond for each pair of carbon atoms, giving a calculated bond order of 1.5 (one and a half bond).
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] Furthermore, bond orders of 1.1 (eleven tenths bond), 4/3 (or 1.333333..., four thirds bond) or 0.5 (half bond), for example, can occur in some molecules and essentially refer to bond strength relative to bonds with order 1.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] In the nitrate anion (NO−3), the bond order for each bond between nitrogen and oxygen is 4/3 (or 1.333333...).
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] Bonding in a dihydrogen cation H+2 can be described as a covalent one-electron bond, thus the bonding between the two hydrogen atoms has bond order of 0.5.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] There are cases where alkene bond order can be non-integer without resonance.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] Notable examples are "cubene" and "quadricyclene".
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] As reported by Garg and Houk in 2026, the bond orders of these unusual alkenes approach 1.5 due to hyperpyramidalization.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] In molecular orbital theory, bond order is defined as half the difference between the number of bonding electrons and the number of antibonding electrons as per the equation below.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] This often but not always yields similar results for bonds near their equilibrium lengths, but it does not work for stretched bonds.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] Bond order is also an index of bond strength and is also used extensively in valence bond theory.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] Generally, the higher the bond order, the stronger the bond.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] Bond orders of one-half may be stable, as shown by the stability of H+2 (bond length 106 pm, bond energy 269 kJ/mol) and He+2 (bond length 108 pm, bond energy 251 kJ/mol).
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] Hückel molecular orbital theory offers another approach for defining bond orders based on molecular orbital coefficients, for planar molecules with delocalized π bonding.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] The theory divides bonding into a sigma framework and a pi system.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] Here the sum extends over π molecular orbitals only, and *ni* is the number of electrons occupying orbital *i* with coefficients *cri* and *csi* on atoms *r* and *s* respectively.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] Assuming a bond order contribution of 1 from the sigma component this gives a total bond order (σ + π) of 5/3 = 1.67 for benzene, rather than the commonly cited bond order of 1.5, showing some degree of ambiguity in how the concept of bond order is defined.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] For more elaborate forms of molecular orbital theory involving larger basis sets, still other definitions have been proposed.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] A standard quantum mechanical definition for bond order has been debated for a long time.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] A comprehensive method to compute bond orders from quantum chemistry calculations was published in 2017.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] The bond order concept is used in molecular dynamics and bond order potentials.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] The magnitude of the bond order is associated with the bond length.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] where *d*1 is the single bond length, *dij* is the bond length experimentally measured, and *b* is a constant, depending on the atoms.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] The value of the constant *b* depends on the atoms.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/bond-order] This definition of bond order is somewhat *ad hoc* and only easy to apply for diatomic molecules.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/homo-and-lumo] In chemistry, **HOMO** and **LUMO** are types of molecular orbitals described at absolute zero.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/homo-and-lumo] The acronyms stand for **highest occupied molecular orbital** and **lowest unoccupied molecular orbital**, respectively.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/homo-and-lumo] HOMO and LUMO are sometimes collectively called the **frontier orbitals**, such as in the frontier molecular orbital theory.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/homo-and-lumo] The energy difference between the HOMO and LUMO is *the HOMO–LUMO gap*.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/homo-and-lumo] Its size can be used to predict the strength and stability of transition metal complexes, as well as the colors they produce in solution.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/homo-and-lumo] As a rule of thumb, the smaller a compound's HOMO–LUMO gap, the less stable the compound.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/homo-and-lumo] The HOMO level is to organic semiconductors roughly what the maximum valence band is to inorganic semiconductors and quantum dots.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/homo-and-lumo] The same analogy can be made between the LUMO level and the conduction band minimum.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/homo-and-lumo] In organometallic chemistry, the size of the LUMO lobe can help predict where addition to pi ligands will occur.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/homo-and-lumo] A *SOMO* is a *singly occupied molecular orbital* such as half-filled HOMO of a radical.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/homo-and-lumo] This abbreviation may also be extended to *semi occupied molecular orbital*.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/homo-and-lumo] If existent, the molecular orbitals at one energy level below the HOMO and one energy level above the LUMO are also found to play a role in frontier molecular orbital theory.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/homo-and-lumo] They are named *NHOMO* for *next-to-highest occupied molecular orbital* and *SLUMO* for *second lowest unoccupied molecular orbital*.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/homo-and-lumo] These are also commonly referred to as HOMO−1 and LUMO+1 respectively.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/linear-combination-of-atomic-orbitals] A **linear combination of atomic orbitals** (**LCAO**) is a quantum superposition of atomic orbitals and a technique for calculating molecular orbitals in quantum chemistry.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/linear-combination-of-atomic-orbitals] In quantum mechanics, electron configurations of atoms are described as wavefunctions.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/linear-combination-of-atomic-orbitals] In a mathematical sense, these wave functions are the basis set of functions, the basis functions, which describe the electrons of a given atom.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/linear-combination-of-atomic-orbitals] In chemical reactions, orbital wavefunctions are modified, i.e. the electron cloud shape is changed, according to the type of atoms participating in the chemical bond.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/linear-combination-of-atomic-orbitals] It was introduced in 1929 by Sir John Lennard-Jones with the description of bonding in the diatomic molecules of the first main row of the periodic table, but had been used earlier by Linus Pauling for H2+.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/linear-combination-of-atomic-orbitals] An initial assumption is that the number of molecular orbitals is equal to the number of atomic orbitals included in the linear expansion.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/linear-combination-of-atomic-orbitals] In a sense, *n* atomic orbitals combine to form *n* molecular orbitals, which can be numbered *i* = 1 to *n* and which may not all be the same.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/linear-combination-of-atomic-orbitals] where $\ \phi _{i}$ is a molecular orbital represented as the sum of *n* atomic orbitals $\ \chi _{r}$ , each multiplied by a corresponding coefficient $\ c_{ri}$ , and *r* (numbered 1 to *n*) represents which atomic orbital is combined in the term.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/linear-combination-of-atomic-orbitals] The coefficients are the weights of the contributions of the n atomic orbitals to the molecular orbital.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/linear-combination-of-atomic-orbitals] The Hartree–Fock method is used to obtain the coefficients of the expansion.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/linear-combination-of-atomic-orbitals] The orbitals are thus expressed as linear combinations of basis functions, and the basis functions are single-electron functions which may or may not be centered on the nuclei of the component atoms of the molecule.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/linear-combination-of-atomic-orbitals] In either case the basis functions are usually also referred to as atomic orbitals (even though only in the former case this name seems to be adequate).
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/linear-combination-of-atomic-orbitals] The atomic orbitals used are typically those of hydrogen-like atoms since these are known analytically i.e.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/linear-combination-of-atomic-orbitals] Slater-type orbitals but other choices are possible such as the Gaussian functions from standard basis sets or the pseudo-atomic orbitals from plane-wave pseudopotentials.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/linear-combination-of-atomic-orbitals] By minimizing the total energy of the system, an appropriate set of coefficients of the linear combinations is determined.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/linear-combination-of-atomic-orbitals] This quantitative approach is now known as the Hartree–Fock method.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/linear-combination-of-atomic-orbitals] However, since the development of computational chemistry, the LCAO method often refers not to an actual optimization of the wave function but to a qualitative discussion which is very useful for predicting and rationalizing results obtained via more modern methods.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/linear-combination-of-atomic-orbitals] In this case, the shape of the molecular orbitals and their respective energies are deduced approximately from comparing the energies of the atomic orbitals of the individual atoms (or molecular fragments) and applying some recipes known as level repulsion and the like.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/linear-combination-of-atomic-orbitals] The graphs that are plotted to make this discussion clearer are called correlation diagrams.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/linear-combination-of-atomic-orbitals] The required atomic orbital energies can come from calculations or directly from experiment via Koopmans' theorem.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/linear-combination-of-atomic-orbitals] This is done by using the symmetry of the molecules and orbitals involved in bonding, and thus is sometimes called *symmetry adapted linear combination* (SALC).
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/linear-combination-of-atomic-orbitals] The first step in this process is assigning a point group to the molecule.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/linear-combination-of-atomic-orbitals] Each operation in the point group is performed upon the molecule.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/linear-combination-of-atomic-orbitals] The number of bonds that are unmoved is the character of that operation.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/linear-combination-of-atomic-orbitals] This reducible representation is decomposed into the sum of irreducible representations.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/linear-combination-of-atomic-orbitals] These irreducible representations correspond to the symmetry of the orbitals involved.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/linear-combination-of-atomic-orbitals] Molecular orbital diagrams provide simple qualitative LCAO treatment.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/linear-combination-of-atomic-orbitals] The Hückel method, the extended Hückel method and the Pariser–Parr–Pople method, provide some quantitative theories.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] In chemistry, **molecular orbital theory** (MO theory or MOT) is a method for describing the electronic structure of molecules using quantum mechanics.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] It was proposed early in the 20th century.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] The MOT explains the paramagnetic nature of O2, which valence bond theory cannot explain.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] In molecular orbital theory, electrons in a molecule are not assigned to individual chemical bonds between atoms, but are treated as moving under the influence of the atomic nuclei in the whole molecule.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] Quantum mechanics describes the spatial and energetic properties of electrons as molecular orbitals that surround two or more atoms in a molecule and contain valence electrons between atoms.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] Molecular orbital theory revolutionized the study of chemical bonding by approximating the states of bonded electrons – the molecular orbitals – as linear combinations of atomic orbitals (LCAO).
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] These approximations are made by applying the density functional theory (DFT) or Hartree–Fock (HF) models to the Schrödinger equation.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] Molecular orbital theory and valence bond theory are the foundational theories of quantum chemistry.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] In the LCAO method, each molecule has a set of molecular orbitals.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] One may determine *cij* coefficients numerically by substituting this equation into the Schrödinger equation and applying the variational principle.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] The variational principle is a mathematical technique used in quantum mechanics to build up the coefficients of each atomic orbital basis.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] A larger coefficient means that the orbital basis is composed more of that particular contributing atomic orbital – hence, the molecular orbital is best characterized by that type.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] This method of quantifying orbital contribution as a linear combination of atomic orbitals is used in computational chemistry.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] An additional unitary transformation can be applied on the system to accelerate the convergence in some computational schemes.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] Molecular orbital theory was seen as a competitor to valence bond theory in the 1930s, before it was realized that the two methods are closely related and that when extended they become equivalent.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] Molecular orbital theory is used to interpret ultraviolet–visible spectroscopy (UV–VIS).
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] Changes to the electronic structure of molecules can be seen by the absorbance of light at specific wavelengths.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] Assignments can be made to these signals indicated by the transition of electrons moving from one orbital at a lower energy to a higher energy orbital.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] The molecular orbital diagram for the final state describes the electronic nature of the molecule in an excited state.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] There are three main requirements for atomic orbital combinations to be suitable as approximate molecular orbitals.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] Atomic orbitals must also overlap within space.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] They cannot combine to form molecular orbitals if they are too far away from one another.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] Atomic orbitals must be at similar energy levels to combine as molecular orbitals.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] Because if the energy difference is great, when the molecular orbitals form, the change in energy becomes small.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] Consequently, there is not enough reduction in energy of electrons to make significant bonding.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] Molecular orbital theory was developed in the years after valence bond theory had been established (1927), primarily through the efforts of Friedrich Hund, Robert Mulliken, John C.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] MO theory was originally called the Hund-Mulliken theory.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] According to physicist and physical chemist Erich Hückel, the first quantitative use of molecular orbital theory was the 1929 paper of Lennard-Jones.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] This paper predicted a triplet ground state for the dioxygen molecule which explained its paramagnetism (see Molecular orbital diagram § Dioxygen) before valence bond theory, which came up with its own explanation in 1931.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] The word *orbital* was introduced by Mulliken in 1932.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] By 1933, the molecular orbital theory had been accepted as a valid and useful theory.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] Erich Hückel applied molecular orbital theory to unsaturated hydrocarbon molecules starting in 1931 with his Hückel molecular orbital (HMO) method for the determination of MO energies for pi electrons, which he applied to conjugated and aromatic hydrocarbons.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] This method provided an explanation of the stability of molecules with six pi-electrons such as benzene.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] The first accurate calculation of a molecular orbital wavefunction was that made by Charles Coulson in 1938 on the hydrogen molecule.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] By 1950, molecular orbitals were completely defined as eigenfunctions (wave functions) of the self-consistent field Hamiltonian and it was at this point that molecular orbital theory became fully rigorous and consistent.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] This rigorous approach is known as the Hartree–Fock method for molecules although it had its origins in calculations on atoms.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] In calculations on molecules, the molecular orbitals are expanded in terms of an atomic orbital basis set, leading to the Roothaan equations.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] This led to the development of many ab initio quantum chemistry methods.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] In parallel, molecular orbital theory was applied in a more approximate manner using some empirically derived parameters in methods now known as semi-empirical quantum chemistry methods.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] The success of Molecular Orbital Theory also spawned ligand field theory, which was developed during the 1930s and 1940s as an alternative to crystal field theory.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] Molecular orbital (MO) theory uses a linear combination of atomic orbitals (LCAO) to represent molecular orbitals resulting from bonds between atoms.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] These are often divided into three types, bonding, antibonding, and non-bonding.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] A bonding orbital concentrates electron density in the region *between* a given pair of atoms, so that its electron density will tend to attract each of the two nuclei toward the other and hold the two atoms together.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] An anti-bonding orbital concentrates electron density "behind" each nucleus (i.e. on the side of each atom which is farthest from the other atom), and so tends to pull each of the two nuclei away from the other and actually weaken the bond between the two nuclei.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] Electrons in non-bonding orbitals tend to be associated with atomic orbitals that do not interact positively or negatively with one another, and electrons in these orbitals neither contribute to nor detract from bond strength.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] Molecular orbitals are further divided according to the types of atomic orbitals they are formed from.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] Chemical substances will form bonding interactions if their orbitals become lower in energy when they interact with each other.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] Different bonding orbitals are distinguished that differ by electron configuration (electron cloud shape) and by energy levels.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] The molecular orbitals of a molecule can be illustrated in molecular orbital diagrams.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] Common bonding orbitals are sigma (σ) orbitals which are symmetric about the bond axis and pi (π) orbitals with a nodal plane along the bond axis.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] Less common are delta (δ) orbitals and phi (φ) orbitals with two and three nodal planes respectively along the bond axis.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] Antibonding orbitals are signified by the addition of an asterisk.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] For example, an antibonding pi orbital may be shown as π*.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] Bond order is the number of chemical bonds between a pair of atoms.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] The bond order of a molecule can be calculated by subtracting the number of electrons in anti-bonding orbitals from the number of bonding orbitals, and the resulting number is then divided by two.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] A molecule is expected to be stable if it has bond order larger than zero.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] It is adequate to consider the valence electron to determine the bond order.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] Because (for principal quantum number *n* > 1) when MOs are derived from 1s AOs, the difference in number of electrons in bonding and anti-bonding molecular orbital is zero.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] So, there is no net effect on bond order if the electron is not the valence one.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] From bond order, one can predict whether a bond between two atoms will form or not.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] For example, the existence of He2 molecule.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] From the molecular orbital diagram, the bond order is ${\textstyle {\frac {1}{2}}(2-2)=0}$ .
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] That means, no bond formation will occur between two He atoms which is seen experimentally.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] It can be detected under very low temperature and pressure molecular beam and has binding energy of approximately 0.001 J/mol.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] Besides, the strength of a bond can also be realized from bond order (BO).
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] As the bond order of H2+ is smaller than H2, it should be less stable which is observed experimentally and can be seen from the bond energy.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] For covalent molecules, the Lewis structure can generally predict the geometry of electron pairs and of the molecule itself, as well as approximately predicting bond angles.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] However, the Lewis structure Does not fully describe the properties of every covalent molecule.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] This becomes clear when the dioxygen (O2) molecule is analyzed.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] The electronic structure of O2 appears to adhere to all the rules governing Lewis theory.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] There is an O=O double bond, and each oxygen atom has eight electrons around it.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] However, this picture does not properly describe the magnetic behavior of oxygen.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] Indeed, when liquid oxygen is poured over a strong magnet, it collects at the poles of the magnet.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] Such attraction to a magnetic field is called paramagnetism, and it arises in molecules that have unpaired electrons.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] And yet, the Lewis structure of O2 indicates that all electrons are paired.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] This discrepancy may be explained by the molecular orbital diagram of O2 (pictured on right).
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] O2 has unpaired electrons, hence it is paramagnetic, and the bonding predicted by Lewis theory still maintains some merit by way of the bond order of 2, which remains the same in both theories.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] Magnetic properties such as these may be characterized experimentally to confirm the predictions of molecular orbital theory.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] Magnetic susceptibility measures the force experienced by a substance in a magnetic field.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] When the weight of a sample is compared to the weight measured in a magnetic field, paramagnetic samples that are attracted to the magnet will appear heavier because of the force exerted by the magnetic field.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] It is possible, then, to calculate the number of unpaired electrons based on the increase in weight.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] MOT provides a global, delocalized perspective on chemical bonding.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] In MO theory, *any* electron in a molecule may be found *anywhere* in the molecule, since quantum conditions allow electrons to travel under the influence of an arbitrarily large number of nuclei, as long as they are in eigenstates permitted by certain quantum rules.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] Thus, when excited with the requisite amount of energy through high-frequency light or other means, electrons can transition to higher-energy molecular orbitals.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] For instance, in the simple case of a hydrogen diatomic molecule, promotion of a single electron from a bonding orbital to an antibonding orbital can occur under UV radiation.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] This promotion weakens the bond between the two hydrogen atoms and can lead to photodissociation, the breaking of a chemical bond due to the absorption of light.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] Although in MO theory *some* molecular orbitals may hold electrons that are more localized between specific pairs of molecular atoms, *other* orbitals may hold electrons that are spread more uniformly over the molecule.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] Thus, overall, bonding is far more delocalized in MO theory, which makes it more applicable to resonant molecules that have equivalent non-integer bond orders than valence bond theory.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] This makes MO theory more useful for the description of extended systems.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] Mulliken, who actively participated in the advent of molecular orbital theory, considers each molecule to be a self-sufficient unit.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] An example is the MO description of benzene, C 6H 6, which is an aromatic hexagonal ring of six carbon atoms and three double bonds.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] In this molecule, 24 of the 30 total valence bonding electrons – 24 coming from carbon atoms and 6 coming from hydrogen atoms – are located in 12 σ (sigma) bonding orbitals, which are located mostly between pairs of atoms (C–C or C–H), similarly to the electrons in the valence bond description.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] However, in benzene the remaining six bonding electrons are located in three π (pi) molecular bonding orbitals that are delocalized around the ring.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] Two of these electrons are in an MO that has equal orbital contributions from all six atoms.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] The other four electrons are in orbitals with vertical nodes at right angles to each other.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] As in the VB theory, all of these six delocalized π electrons reside in a larger space that exists above and below the ring plane.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] All carbon–carbon bonds in benzene are chemically equivalent.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] In MO theory this is a direct consequence of the fact that the three molecular π orbitals combine and evenly spread the extra six electrons over six carbon atoms.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] In molecules such as methane, CH 4, the eight valence electrons are found in four MOs that are spread out over all five atoms.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] It is possible to transform the MOs into four localized sp3 orbitals.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] Linus Pauling, in 1931, hybridized the carbon 2s and 2p orbitals so that they pointed directly at the hydrogen 1s basis functions and featured maximal overlap.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] However, the delocalized MO description is more appropriate for predicting ionization energies and the positions of spectral absorption bands.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] When methane is ionized, a single electron is taken from the valence MOs, which can come from the s bonding or the triply degenerate p bonding levels, yielding two ionization energies.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] In comparison, the explanation in valence bond theory is more complicated.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] When one electron is removed from an sp3 orbital, resonance is invoked between four valence bond structures, each of which has a single one-electron bond and three two-electron bonds.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] Triply degenerate T2 and A1 ionized states (CH4+) are produced from different linear combinations of these four structures.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] The difference in energy between the ionized and ground state gives the two ionization energies.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] This and other spectroscopic data for molecules are well explained in MO theory, with an emphasis on electronic states associated with multicenter orbitals, including mixing of orbitals premised on principles of orbital symmetry matching.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] The same MO principles also naturally explain some electrical phenomena, such as high electrical conductivity in the planar direction of the hexagonal atomic sheets that exist in graphite.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital-theory] This results from continuous band overlap of half-filled p orbitals and explains electrical conduction.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] In chemistry, a **molecular orbital** is a mathematical function describing the location and wave-like behavior of an electron in a molecule.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] This function can be used to calculate chemical and physical properties such as the probability of finding an electron in any specific region.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] The terms *atomic orbital* and *molecular orbital* were introduced by Robert S.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Mulliken in 1932 to mean *one-electron orbital wave functions*.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] At an elementary level, they are used to describe the *region* of space in which a function has a significant amplitude.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] In an isolated atom, the orbital electrons' location is determined by functions called atomic orbitals.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] When multiple atoms combine chemically into a molecule by forming a valence chemical bond, the electrons' locations are determined by the molecule as a whole, so the atomic orbitals combine to form molecular orbitals.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] The electrons from the constituent atoms occupy the molecular orbitals.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Mathematically, molecular orbitals are an approximate solution to the Schrödinger equation for the electrons in the field of the molecule's atomic nuclei.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] They are usually constructed by combining atomic orbitals or hybrid orbitals from each atom of the molecule, or other molecular orbitals from groups of atoms.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] They can be quantitatively calculated using the Hartree–Fock or self-consistent field (SCF) methods.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] A molecular orbital (MO) can be used to represent the regions in a molecule where an electron occupying that orbital is likely to be found.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Molecular orbitals are approximate solutions to the Schrödinger equation for the electrons in the electric field of the molecule's atomic nuclei.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] However calculating the orbitals directly from this equation is far too intractable a problem.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Instead they are obtained from the combination of atomic orbitals, which predict the location of an electron in an atom.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] A molecular orbital can specify the electron configuration of a molecule: the spatial distribution and energy of one (or one pair of) electron(s).
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Most commonly a MO is represented as a linear combination of atomic orbitals (the LCAO-MO method), especially in qualitative or very approximate usage.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] They are invaluable in providing a simple model of bonding in molecules, understood through molecular orbital theory.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Most present-day methods in computational chemistry begin by calculating the MOs of the system.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] A molecular orbital describes the behavior of one electron in the electric field generated by the nuclei and some average distribution of the other electrons.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] In the case of two electrons occupying the same orbital, the Pauli principle demands that they have opposite spin.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Necessarily this is an approximation, and highly accurate descriptions of the molecular electronic wave function do not have orbitals (see configuration interaction).
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Molecular orbitals are, in general, delocalized throughout the entire molecule.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Moreover, if the molecule has symmetry elements, its nondegenerate molecular orbitals are either symmetric or antisymmetric with respect to any of these symmetries.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] In other words, the application of a symmetry operation **S** (e.g., a reflection, rotation, or inversion) to molecular orbital ψ results in the molecular orbital being unchanged or reversing its mathematical sign: **S**ψ = ±ψ.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] In planar molecules, for example, molecular orbitals are either symmetric (sigma) or antisymmetric (pi) with respect to reflection in the molecular plane.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] If molecules with degenerate orbital energies are also considered, a more general statement that molecular orbitals form bases for the irreducible representations of the molecule's symmetry group holds.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] In contrast to these symmetry-adapted *canonical* molecular orbitals, localized molecular orbitals can be formed by applying certain mathematical transformations to the canonical orbitals.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] The advantage of this approach is that the orbitals will correspond more closely to the "bonds" of a molecule as depicted by a Lewis structure.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] As a disadvantage, the energy levels of these localized orbitals no longer have physical meaning.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] (The discussion in the rest of this article will focus on canonical molecular orbitals.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Molecular orbitals arise from allowed interactions between atomic orbitals, which are allowed if the symmetries (determined from group theory) of the atomic orbitals are compatible with each other.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Efficiency of atomic orbital interactions is determined from the overlap (a measure of how well two orbitals constructively interact with one another) between two atomic orbitals, which is significant if the atomic orbitals are close in energy.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Finally, the number of molecular orbitals formed must be equal to the number of atomic orbitals in the atoms being combined to form the molecule.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] For an imprecise, but qualitatively useful, discussion of the molecular structure, the molecular orbitals can be obtained from the "Linear combination of atomic orbitals molecular orbital method" ansatz.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Here, the molecular orbitals are expressed as linear combinations of atomic orbitals.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Molecular orbitals were first introduced by Friedrich Hund and Robert S.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] The linear combination of atomic orbitals or "LCAO" approximation for molecular orbitals was introduced in 1929 by Sir John Lennard-Jones.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] His ground-breaking paper showed how to derive the electronic structure of the fluorine and oxygen molecules from quantum principles.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] This qualitative approach to molecular orbital theory is part of the start of modern quantum chemistry.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Linear combinations of atomic orbitals (LCAO) can be used to estimate the molecular orbitals that are formed upon bonding between the molecule's constituent atoms.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Similar to an atomic orbital, a Schrödinger equation, which describes the behavior of an electron, can be constructed for a molecular orbital as well.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Linear combinations of atomic orbitals, or the sums and differences of the atomic wavefunctions, provide approximate solutions to the Hartree–Fock equations which correspond to the independent-particle approximation of the molecular Schrödinger equation.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] where $\Psi$ and $\Psi ^{*}$ are the molecular wavefunctions for the bonding and antibonding molecular orbitals, respectively, $\psi _{a}$ and $\psi _{b}$ are the atomic wavefunctions from atoms a and b, respectively, and $c_{a}$ and $c_{b}$ are adjustable coefficients.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] These coefficients can be positive or negative, depending on the energies and symmetries of the individual atomic orbitals.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] As the two atoms become closer together, their atomic orbitals overlap to produce areas of high electron density, and, as a consequence, molecular orbitals are formed between the two atoms.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] The atoms are held together by the electrostatic attraction between the positively charged nuclei and the negatively charged electrons occupying bonding molecular orbitals.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] When atomic orbitals interact, the resulting molecular orbital can be of three types: bonding, antibonding, or non bonding.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] The type of interaction between atomic orbitals can be further categorized by the molecular-orbital symmetry labels σ (sigma), π (pi), δ (delta), φ (phi), γ (gamma) etc.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] These are the Greek letters corresponding to the atomic orbitals s, p, d, f and g respectively.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] The number of nodal planes containing the internuclear axis between the atoms concerned is zero for σ MOs, one for π, two for δ, three for φ and four for γ.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] A MO with σ symmetry results from the interaction of either two atomic s-orbitals or two atomic pz-orbitals.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] An MO will have σ-symmetry if the orbital is symmetric with respect to the axis joining the two nuclear centers, the internuclear axis.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] This means that rotation of the MO about the internuclear axis does not result in a phase change.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] A σ* orbital, sigma antibonding orbital, also maintains the same phase when rotated about the internuclear axis.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] The σ* orbital has a nodal plane that is between the nuclei and perpendicular to the internuclear axis.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] A MO with π symmetry results from the interaction of either two atomic px orbitals or py orbitals.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] An MO will have π symmetry if the orbital is asymmetric with respect to rotation about the internuclear axis.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] This means that rotation of the MO about the internuclear axis will result in a phase change.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] There is one nodal plane containing the internuclear axis, if real orbitals are considered.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] A π* orbital, pi antibonding orbital, will also produce a phase change when rotated about the internuclear axis.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] The π* orbital also has a second nodal plane between the nuclei.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] A MO with δ symmetry results from the interaction of two atomic dxy or dx2-y2 orbitals.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Because these molecular orbitals involve low-energy d atomic orbitals, they are seen in transition-metal complexes.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] A δ bonding orbital has two nodal planes containing the internuclear axis, and a δ* antibonding orbital also has a third nodal plane between the nuclei.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Theoretical chemists have conjectured that higher-order bonds, such as phi bonds corresponding to overlap of f atomic orbitals, are possible.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] There is no known example of a molecule purported to contain a phi bond.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] For molecules that possess a center of inversion (centrosymmetric molecules) there are additional labels of symmetry that can be applied to molecular orbitals.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] If inversion through the center of symmetry in a molecule results in the same phases for the molecular orbital, then the MO is said to have gerade (g) symmetry, from the German word for even.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] If inversion through the center of symmetry in a molecule results in a phase change for the molecular orbital, then the MO is said to have ungerade (u) symmetry, from the German word for odd.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] For a bonding MO with σ-symmetry, the orbital is σg (s' + s'' is symmetric), while an antibonding MO with σ-symmetry the orbital is σu, because inversion of s' – s'' is antisymmetric.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] The qualitative approach of MO analysis uses a molecular orbital diagram to visualize bonding interactions in a molecule.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] In this type of diagram, the molecular orbitals are represented by horizontal lines; the higher a line the higher the energy of the orbital, and degenerate orbitals are placed on the same level with a space between them.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] For more complicated molecules, the wave mechanics approach loses utility in a qualitative understanding of bonding (although is still necessary for a quantitative approach).
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Arrange the SALCs of each molecular fragment in order of energy, noting first whether they stem from *s*, *p*, or *d* orbitals (and put them in the order *s* < *p* < *d*), and then their number of internuclear nodes.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Combine SALCs of the same symmetry type from the two fragments, and from N SALCs form N molecular orbitals.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Estimate the relative energies of the molecular orbitals from considerations of overlap and relative energies of the parent orbitals, and draw the levels on a molecular orbital energy level diagram (showing the origin of the orbitals).
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Confirm, correct, and revise this qualitative order by carrying out a molecular orbital calculation by using commercial software.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Molecular orbitals are said to be degenerate if they have the same energy.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] For example, in the homonuclear diatomic molecules of the first ten elements, the molecular orbitals derived from the px and the py atomic orbitals result in two degenerate bonding orbitals (of low energy) and two degenerate antibonding orbitals (of high energy).
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] In an ionic bond, oppositely charged ions are bonded by electrostatic attraction.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] It is possible to describe ionic bonds with molecular orbital theory by treating them as extremely polar bonds.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Their bonding orbitals are very close in energy to the atomic orbitals of the anion.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] They are also very similar in character to the anion's atomic orbitals, which means the electrons are completely shifted to the anion.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] In computer diagrams, the orbitals are centered on the anion's core.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] The bond order, or number of bonds, of a molecule can be determined by combining the number of electrons in bonding and antibonding molecular orbitals.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] A pair of electrons in a bonding orbital creates a bond, whereas a pair of electrons in an antibonding orbital negates a bond.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] For example, N2, with eight electrons in bonding orbitals and two electrons in antibonding orbitals, has a bond order of three, which constitutes a triple bond.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Bond strength is proportional to bond order—a greater amount of bonding produces a more stable bond—and bond length is inversely proportional to it—a stronger bond is shorter.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] There are rare exceptions to the requirement of molecule having a positive bond order.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Although Be2 has a bond order of 0 according to MO analysis, there is experimental evidence of a highly unstable Be2 molecule having a bond length of 245 pm and bond energy of 10 kJ/mol.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] The highest occupied molecular orbital and lowest unoccupied molecular orbital are often referred to as the HOMO and LUMO, respectively.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] The difference of the energies of the HOMO and LUMO is called the HOMO–LUMO gap.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] This notion is often the matter of confusion in literature and should be considered with caution.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] In addition, the HOMO–LUMO gap can be related to a bulk-material band gap or transport gap, which is usually much smaller than the single-molecule fundamental gap.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Homonuclear diatomic MOs contain equal contributions from each atomic orbital in the basis set.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] This is shown in the homonuclear diatomic MO diagrams for H2, He2, and Li2, all of which containing symmetric orbitals.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] As a simple MO example, consider the electrons in a hydrogen molecule, H2 (see molecular orbital diagram), with the two atoms labelled H' and H".
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] The lowest-energy atomic orbitals, 1s' and 1s", do not transform according to the symmetries of the molecule.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] The symmetric combination (called a bonding orbital) is lower in energy than the basis orbitals, and the antisymmetric combination (called an antibonding orbital) is higher.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Because the H2 molecule has two electrons, they can both go in the bonding orbital, making the system lower in energy (hence more stable) than two free hydrogen atoms.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] The bond order is equal to the number of bonding electrons minus the number of antibonding electrons, divided by 2.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] In this example, there are 2 electrons in the bonding orbital and none in the antibonding orbital; the bond order is 1, and there is a single bond between the two hydrogen atoms.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] On the other hand, consider the hypothetical molecule of He2 with the atoms labeled He' and He".
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] As with H2, the lowest energy atomic orbitals are the 1s' and 1s", and do not transform according to the symmetries of the molecule, while the symmetry adapted atomic orbitals do.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] The symmetric combination—the bonding orbital—is lower in energy than the basis orbitals, and the antisymmetric combination—the antibonding orbital—is higher.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Unlike H2, with two valence electrons, He2 has four in its neutral ground state.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Two electrons fill the lower-energy bonding orbital, σg(1s), while the remaining two fill the higher-energy antibonding orbital, σu*(1s).
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Thus, the resulting electron density around the molecule does not support the formation of a bond between the two atoms; without a stable bond holding the atoms together, the molecule would not be expected to exist.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Another way of looking at it is that there are two bonding electrons and two antibonding electrons; therefore, the bond order is 0 and no bond exists (the molecule has one bound state supported by the Van der Waals potential).
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Dilithium Li2 is formed from the overlap of the 1s and 2s atomic orbitals (the basis set) of two Li atoms.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Each Li atom contributes three electrons for bonding interactions, and the six electrons fill the three MOs of lowest energy, σg(1s), σu*(1s), and σg(2s).
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Using the equation for bond order, it is found that dilithium has a bond order of one, a single bond.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Considering a hypothetical molecule of He2, since the basis set of atomic orbitals is the same as in the case of H2, we find that both the bonding and antibonding orbitals are filled, so there is no energy advantage to the pair.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] HeH would have a slight energy advantage, but not as much as H2 + 2 He, so the molecule is very unstable and exists only briefly before decomposing into hydrogen and helium.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] In general, we find that atoms such as He that have full energy shells rarely bond with other atoms.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Except for short-lived Van der Waals complexes, there are very few noble gas compounds known.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] While MOs for homonuclear diatomic molecules contain equal contributions from each interacting atomic orbital, MOs for heteronuclear diatomics contain different atomic orbital contributions.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Orbital interactions to produce bonding or antibonding orbitals in heteronuclear diatomics occur if there is sufficient overlap between atomic orbitals as determined by their symmetries and similarity in orbital energies.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] In hydrogen fluoride HF overlap between the H 1s and F 2s orbitals is allowed by symmetry but the difference in energy between the two atomic orbitals prevents them from interacting to create a molecular orbital.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Overlap between the H 1s and F 2pz orbitals is also symmetry allowed, and these two atomic orbitals have a small energy separation.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Thus, they interact, leading to creation of σ and σ* MOs and a molecule with a bond order of 1.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Since HF is a non-centrosymmetric molecule, the symmetry labels g and u do not apply to its molecular orbitals.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] To obtain quantitative values for the molecular energy levels, one needs to have molecular orbitals that are such that the configuration interaction (CI) expansion converges fast towards the full CI limit.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] The most common method to obtain such functions is the Hartree–Fock method, which expresses the molecular orbitals as eigenfunctions of the Fock operator.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] One usually solves this problem by expanding the molecular orbitals as linear combinations of Gaussian functions centered on the atomic nuclei (see linear combination of atomic orbitals and basis set (chemistry)).
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] The equation for the coefficients of these linear combinations is a generalized eigenvalue equation known as the Roothaan equations, which are in fact a particular representation of the Hartree–Fock equation.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] There are a number of programs in which quantum chemical calculations of MOs can be performed, including Spartan.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Simple accounts often suggest that experimental molecular orbital energies can be obtained by the methods of ultra-violet photoelectron spectroscopy for valence orbitals and X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy for core orbitals.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] This, however, is incorrect as these experiments measure the ionization energy, the difference in energy between the molecule and one of the ions resulting from the removal of one electron.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] Ionization energies are linked approximately to orbital energies by Koopmans' theorem.
[src:molecular-orbital-theory/molecular-orbital] While the agreement between these two values can be close for some molecules, it can be very poor in other cases.
